# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: logspace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:logspace/l-complexity] In computational complexity theory, **L** (also known as **LSPACE**, **LOGSPACE** or **DLOGSPACE**) is the complexity class containing decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine using a logarithmic amount of writable memory space.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Formally, the Turing machine has two tapes, one of which encodes the input and can only be read, whereas the other tape has logarithmic size but can be written as well as read.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Logarithmic space is sufficient to hold a constant number of pointers into the input and a logarithmic number of Boolean flags, and many basic logspace algorithms use the memory in this way.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Every non-trivial problem in **L** is complete under log-space reductions, so weaker reductions are required to identify meaningful notions of **L**-completeness, the most common being first-order reductions.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] A 2004 result by Omer Reingold shows that USTCON, the problem of whether there exists a path between two vertices in a given undirected graph, is in **L**, showing that **L** = **SL**, since USTCON is **SL**-complete.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] One consequence of this is a simple logical characterization of **L**: it contains precisely those languages expressible in first-order logic with an added commutative transitive closure operator (in graph theoretical terms, this turns every connected component into a clique).
[src:logspace/l-complexity] This result has application to database query languages: *data complexity* of a query is defined as the complexity of answering a fixed query considering the data size as the variable input.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] For this measure, queries against relational databases with complete information (having no notion of nulls) as expressed for instance in relational algebra are in **L**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Important open problems include whether **L** = **P**, and whether **L** = **NL**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] It is not even known whether **L** = **NP**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] The related class of function problems is **FL**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] **FL** is often used to define logspace reductions.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Just as how **P** has several random versions: **BPP**, **ZPP**, **PP**, and **RP**, there are several random versions of **L**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] It is contained in **NC***2*, which is contained in **P**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Also, it must always run in polynomial time (since otherwise we would just get **NL**).
[src:logspace/l-complexity] It is strongly suspected that **RL** = **L**.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Both **BPL** and **RL** are contained in Steve's Class.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] It contains **BPL**, and is contained by **NC***2*.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] The main idea of logspace is that one can store a polynomial-magnitude number in logspace and use it to remember pointers to a position of the input.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] The logspace class is therefore useful to model computation where the input is too big to fit in the RAM of a computer.
[src:logspace/l-complexity] Long DNA sequences and databases are good examples of problems where only a constant part of the input will be in RAM at a given time and where we have pointers to compute the next part of the input to inspect, thus using only logarithmic memory.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] In computational complexity theory, a **log-space reduction** is a reduction computable by a deterministic Turing machine using logarithmic space.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Conceptually, this means the Turing machine can keep a constant number of pointers into the input, along with a logarithmic number of fixed-size integers.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] It is possible that such a machine may not have space to write down its own output, so the only requirement is that any given bit of the output be computable in log-space.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Formally, this reduction is executed via a log-space transducer.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Such a machine has polynomially-many configurations, so log-space reductions are also polynomial-time reductions.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] It is an open question if the NP-complete problems are different with respect to log-space and polynomial-time reductions.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] However, other subclasses of P such as NC may not be closed under Turing reductions, and so many-one reductions must be used.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Just as polynomial-time reductions are useless within P and its subclasses, log-space reductions are useless to distinguish problems in L and its subclasses; in particular, every non-empty, non-full problem in L is trivially L-complete under log-space reductions.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] While even weaker reductions exist, they are not often used in practice, because complexity classes smaller than L (that is, strictly contained or thought to be strictly contained in L) receive relatively little attention.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] The tools available to designers of log-space reductions have been greatly expanded by the result that L = SL; see SL for a list of some SL-complete problems that can now be used as subroutines in log-space reductions.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Intuitively, the first condition states that the function creates outputs that are short enough, such that creating a single pointer on the output will take only logspace.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] That condition is necessary in order for pointers on the output to exist at all.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] The second condition states that any *particular* output location is computable in logspace.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] The third condition states that checking if a pointer is a valid pointer is decidable in logspace.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Such a machine is usually called a **logspace transducer**.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Note that such a machine, if it halts, must halt in polynomial steps, since its work tape has log-length.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Therefore its output length is polynomially bounded.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] One intuition is that such a function can be computed by a program that can only keep a constant number of pointers to the input, and a constant number of counters that can only contain integers of size ${\mathsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] This is because a counter machine with a constant number of counters that count up to $f(n)$ is equivalent to a Turing machine with space complexity $O(\log f(n))$ .
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] The most important property of logspace computability is that, if functions $f,g$ are logspace computable, then so is their composition $g\circ f$ .
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] This allows the concept of logspace reduction to be transitive.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Given two logspace transducers, their composition is still a logspace transducer: feed the output from one transducer (A→B) to another (B→C).
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] At first glance, this seems incorrect because intuitively, the A→C transducer needs to store the output tape from the A→B transducer onto the work tape, in order to feed it into the B→C reducer, but this is not necessary, by the following construction.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Define the A→C transducer as follows: It simulates the operations of B→C transducer.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Every time the B→C transducer needs to make a read, the A→C transducer re-runs the A→B transducer to re-compute only the exact output bit that is needed, and so only one bit of the output of the A→B transducer needs to be stored at any moment.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] A language L is **logspace (many-one) reducible** to another language $L'$ , notated as $L\leq _{l}L'$ , if there exists an implicitly logspace computable function f such that $x\in L\iff f(x)\in L'$ .
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] This is a transitive relation, because logspace computability is closed under composition, as previously shown.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] A language L is **NL-complete** if it is both in NL and any language in NL is logspace reducible to it.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Most naturally occurring polynomial-time reductions in complexity theory are logspace reductions.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] In particular, this is true for the standard proof showing that the SAT problem is NP-complete, and that the circuit value problem is P-complete.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] This is also often the case for showing that the true quantified Boolean formula problem is PSPACE-complete.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] This is because the need for memory in such reduction constructions is for counting up to $p(n)$ for some polynomial p in the input length n , and this can be done in logarithmic space.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] While logspace many-one reduction implies polynomial time many-one reduction, it is unknown whether this is an equivalence, or whether there are problems that are NP-complete under polynomial time reduction, but not under logspace reduction.
[src:logspace/log-space-reduction] Any solution to this problem would solve this problem: Are deterministic linear bounded automata equivalent to nondeterministic linear bounded automata?
[src:logspace/nl-complete] In computational complexity theory, **NL-complete** is a complexity class containing the languages that are complete for **NL**, the class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine using a logarithmic amount of memory space.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] The NL-complete languages are the most "difficult" or "expressive" problems in **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] If a deterministic algorithm exists for solving any one of the NL-complete problems in logarithmic memory space, then **NL** = **L**.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] Formally, a decision problem is NL-complete when it belongs to **NL**, and has the additional property that every other decision problem in **NL** can be reduced to it.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] Unless otherwise specified, the reductions in this definition are assumed to be many-one reductions by a deterministic logarithmic-space algorithm.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] If an NL-complete language *X* could belong to **L**, then so would every other language *Y* in **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] For, suppose (by NL-completeness) that there existed a deterministic logspace reduction *r* that maps an instance *y* of problem *Y* to an instance *x* of problem *X*, and also (by the assumption that *X* is in **L**) that there exists a deterministic logspace algorithm *A* for solving problem *X*.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] With these assumptions, a problem *y* in language Y could be solved in logarithmic space by an algorithm that simulates the behavior of algorithm *A* on input *r*(*y*), using the reduction algorithm to simulate each access to the read-only tape for *r*(*y*).
[src:logspace/nl-complete] It follows from the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem that, if a language is co-NL-complete (that is, if its complement is NL-complete) then the language is also NL-complete itself.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] One important NL-complete problem is ST-connectivity (or "Reachability") (Papadimitriou 1994 Thrm.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] 16.2), the problem of determining whether, given a directed graph *G* and two nodes *s* and *t* on that graph, there is a path from *s* to *t*.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] ST-connectivity can be seen to be in **NL**, because we start at the node *s* and nondeterministically walk to every other reachable node.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] ST-connectivity can be seen to be NL-hard by considering the computation state graph of any other **NL** algorithm, and considering that the other algorithm will accept if and only if there is a (nondetermistic) path from the starting state to an accepting state.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] Another important NL-complete problem is 2-satisfiability (Papadimitriou 1994 Thrm.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] 16.3), the problem of determining whether a boolean formula in conjunctive normal form with two variables per clause is satisfiable.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] The problem of unique decipherability of a given variable-length code was shown to be co-NL-complete by Rytter (1986); Rytter used a variant of the Sardinas–Patterson algorithm to show that the complementary problem, finding a string that has multiple ambiguous decodings, belongs to **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] Because of the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem, it follows that unique decipherability is also NL-complete.
[src:logspace/nl-complete] Additional NL-complete problems on propositional logic, algebra, linear system, graph, finite automata, context-free grammar are listed in Jones (1976).
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] In computational complexity theory, **NL** (**N**ondeterministic **L**ogarithmic-space) is the complexity class containing decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine using a logarithmic amount of memory space.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Important results in complexity theory allow us to relate this complexity class with other classes, telling us about the relative power of the resources involved.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Results in the field of algorithms, on the other hand, tell us which problems can be solved with this resource.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Like much of complexity theory, many important questions about **NL** are still open (see Unsolved problems in computer science).
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Occasionally **NL** is referred to as **RL** due to its probabilistic definition below; however, this name is more frequently used to refer to randomized logarithmic space, which is not known to equal **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] There are several equivalent definitions of the **NL** class.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Suppose *C* is the complexity class of decision problems solvable in logarithmithic space with probabilistic Turing machines that never accept incorrectly but are allowed to reject incorrectly less than 1/3 of the time; this is called *one-sided error*.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] The constant 1/3 is arbitrary; any *x* with 0 ≤ *x* < 1/2 would suffice.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Notice that *C*, unlike its deterministic counterpart **L**, is not limited to polynomial time, because although it has a polynomial number of configurations it can use randomness to escape an infinite loop.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] If we do limit it to polynomial time, we get the class **RL**, which is contained in but not known or believed to equal **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] There is a simple algorithm that establishes that *C* = **NL**.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] To show that **NL** is contained in *C*, we simply take an **NL** algorithm and choose a random computation path of length *n*, and execute this 2*n* times.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Because no computation path exceeds length *n*, and because there are 2*n* computation paths in all, we have a good chance of hitting the accepting one (bounded below by a constant).
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] The only problem is that we don't have room in log space for a binary counter that goes up to 2*n*.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] To get around this we replace it with a *randomized* counter, which simply flips *n* coins and stops and rejects if they all land on heads.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Since this event has probability 2−*n*, we expect to take 2*n* steps on average before stopping.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It only needs to keep a running total of the number of heads in a row it sees, which it can count in log space.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Because of the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem, according to which NL is closed under complements, the one-sided error in these probabilistic computations can be replaced by zero-sided error.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] That is, these problems can be solved by probabilistic Turing machines that use logarithmic space and never make errors.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] The corresponding complexity class that also requires the machine to use only polynomial time is called ZPLP.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Thus, when we only look at space, it seems that randomization and nondeterminism are equally powerful.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] In words, it means that if a sentence is in the language, then there exists a polynomial-length proof that it is in the language.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It does not say anything about the case where the sentence is *not* in the language, though by the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem, it is clear that there exists some verifier that can verify both $x\in L$ and $x\not \in L$ .
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Note that the read-once condition is necessary.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] If the verifier can read forwards and backwards, this extends the class to the **NP** class.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Cem Say and Abuzer Yakaryılmaz have proven that the deterministic logarithmic-space Turing machine in the statement above can be replaced by a bounded-error probabilistic constant-space Turing machine that is allowed to use only a constant number of random bits.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] In descriptive complexity theory, **NL** is defined as those languages expressible in first-order logic with an added transitive closure operator.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] The class NL is closed under the operations complementation, union, and therefore intersection, concatenation, and Kleene star.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] A problem is **NL-complete** if it is **NL**, and any problem in **NL** is log-space reducible to it.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Problems that are known to be **NL**-complete including ST-connectivity and 2-satisfiability.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] ST-connectivity asks, for nodes *S* and *T* in a directed graph, whether *T* is reachable from *S*.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] 2-satisfiability asks, given a propositional formula of which each clause is the disjunction of two literals, if there is a variable assignment that makes the formula true.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It is known that NL is contained in P, since there is a polynomial-time algorithm for 2-satisfiability, but it is not known whether NL = P or whether L = NL.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It is known that NL = co-NL, where co-NL is the class of languages whose complements are in NL.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] This result (the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem) was independently discovered by Neil Immerman and Róbert Szelepcsényi in 1987; they received the 1995 Gödel Prize for this work.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] In circuit complexity, NL can be placed within the NC hierarchy.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It is known that NL is equal to ZPL, the class of problems solvable by randomized algorithms in logarithmic space and unbounded time, with no error.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] It is not, however, known or believed to be equal to RLP or ZPLP, the polynomial-time restrictions of RL and ZPL, which some authors refer to as RL and ZPL.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] We can relate NL to deterministic space using Savitch's theorem, which tells us that any nondeterministic algorithm can be simulated by a deterministic machine in at most quadratically more space.
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] This was the strongest deterministic-space inclusion known in 1994 (Papadimitriou 1994 Problem 16.4.10, "Symmetric space").
[src:logspace/nl-complexity] Since larger space classes are not affected by quadratic increases, the nondeterministic and deterministic classes are known to be equal, so that for example we have PSPACE = NPSPACE.
[src:logspace/reachability] In graph theory, **reachability** refers to the ability to get from one vertex to another within a graph.
[src:logspace/reachability] A vertex s can reach a vertex t (and t is reachable from s ) if there exists a sequence of adjacent vertices (i.e. a walk) which starts with s and ends with t .
[src:logspace/reachability] In an undirected graph, reachability between all pairs of vertices can be determined by identifying the connected components of the graph.
[src:logspace/reachability] Any pair of vertices in such a graph can reach each other if and only if they belong to the same connected component; therefore, in such a graph, reachability is symmetric ( s reaches t iff t reaches s ).
[src:logspace/reachability] The connected components of an undirected graph can be identified in linear time.
[src:logspace/reachability] The remainder of this article focuses on the more difficult problem of determining pairwise reachability in a directed graph (which, incidentally, need not be symmetric).
[src:logspace/reachability] If G is acyclic, then its reachability relation is a partial order; any partial order may be defined in this way, for instance as the reachability relation of its transitive reduction.
[src:logspace/reachability] A noteworthy consequence of this is that since partial orders are anti-symmetric, if s can reach t , then we know that t *cannot* reach s .
[src:logspace/reachability] Intuitively, if we could travel from s to t and back to s , then G would contain a cycle, contradicting that it is acyclic.
[src:logspace/reachability] If G is directed but *not* acyclic (i.e. it contains at least one cycle), then its reachability relation will correspond to a preorder instead of a partial order.
[src:logspace/reachability] Algorithms for determining reachability fall into two classes: those that require preprocessing and those that do not.
[src:logspace/reachability] If you have only one (or a few) queries to make, it may be more efficient to forgo the use of more complex data structures and compute the reachability of the desired pair directly.
[src:logspace/reachability] This can be accomplished in linear time using algorithms such as breadth first search or iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:logspace/reachability] If you will be making many queries, then a more sophisticated method may be used; the exact choice of method depends on the nature of the graph being analysed.
[src:logspace/reachability] In exchange for preprocessing time and some extra storage space, we can create a data structure which can then answer reachability queries on any pair of vertices in as low as $O(1)$ time.
[src:logspace/reachability] Three different algorithms and data structures for three different, increasingly specialized situations are outlined below.
[src:logspace/reachability] The Floyd–Warshall algorithm can be used to compute the transitive closure of any directed graph, which gives rise to the reachability relation as in the definition, above.
[src:logspace/reachability] The algorithm requires $O(|V|^{3})$ time and $O(|V|^{2})$ space in the worst case.
[src:logspace/reachability] This algorithm is not solely interested in reachability as it also computes the shortest path distance between all pairs of vertices.
[src:logspace/reachability] For graphs containing negative cycles, shortest paths may be undefined, but reachability between pairs can still be noted.
[src:logspace/reachability] For planar digraphs, a much faster method is available, as described by Mikkel Thorup in 2004.
[src:logspace/reachability] This method can answer reachability queries on a planar graph in $O(1)$ time after spending $O(n\log {n})$ preprocessing time to create a data structure of $O(n\log {n})$ size.
[src:logspace/reachability] This algorithm can also supply approximate shortest path distances, as well as route information.
[src:logspace/reachability] The overall approach is to associate with each vertex a relatively small set of so-called separator paths such that any path from a vertex v to any other vertex w must go through at least one of the separators associated with v or w .
[src:logspace/reachability] An outline of the reachability related sections follows.
[src:logspace/reachability] Given a graph G , the algorithm begins by organizing the vertices into layers starting from an arbitrary vertex $v_{0}$ .
[src:logspace/reachability] The layers are built in alternating steps by first considering all vertices reachable *from* the previous step (starting with just $v_{0}$ ) and then all vertices which reach *to* the previous step until all vertices have been assigned to a layer.
[src:logspace/reachability] By construction of the layers, every vertex appears at most two layers, and every directed path, or dipath, in G is contained within two adjacent layers $L_{i}$ and $L_{i+1}$ .
[src:logspace/reachability] Let k be the last layer created, that is, the lowest value for k such that $\bigcup _{i=0}^{k}L_{i}=V$ .
[src:logspace/reachability] The graph is then re-expressed as a series of digraphs $G_{0},G_{1},\ldots ,G_{k-1}$ where each $G_{i}=r_{i}\cup L_{i}\cup L_{i+1}$ and where $r_{i}$ is the contraction of all previous levels $L_{0}\ldots L_{i-1}$ into a single vertex.
[src:logspace/reachability] For each $G_{i}$ , three separators are identified which, when removed, break the graph into three components which each contain at most $1/2$ the vertices of the original.
[src:logspace/reachability] As $G_{i}$ is built from two layers of opposed dipaths, each separator may consist of up to 2 dipaths, for a total of up to 6 dipaths over all of the separators.
[src:logspace/reachability] The proof that such separators can always be found is related to the Planar Separator Theorem of Lipton and Tarjan, and these separators can be located in linear time.
[src:logspace/reachability] For each $Q\in S$ , the directed nature of Q provides for a natural indexing of its vertices from the start to the end of the path.
[src:logspace/reachability] For each vertex v in $G_{i}$ , we locate the first vertex in Q reachable by v , and the last vertex in Q that reaches to v .
[src:logspace/reachability] That is, we are looking at how early into Q we can get from v , and how far we can stay in Q and still get back to v .
[src:logspace/reachability] This information is stored with each v .
[src:logspace/reachability] Then for any pair of vertices u and w , u can reach w *via* Q if u connects to Q earlier than w connects from Q .
[src:logspace/reachability] Every vertex is labelled as above for each step of the recursion which builds $G_{0}\ldots ,G_{k}$ .
[src:logspace/reachability] As this recursion has logarithmic depth, a total of $O(\log {n})$ extra information is stored per vertex.
[src:logspace/reachability] From this point, a logarithmic time query for reachability is as simple as looking over each pair of labels for a common, suitable Q .
[src:logspace/reachability] The original paper then works to tune the query time down to $O(1)$ .
[src:logspace/reachability] In summarizing the analysis of this method, first consider that the layering approach partitions the vertices so that each vertex is considered only $O(1)$ times.
[src:logspace/reachability] The separator phase of the algorithm breaks the graph into components which are at most $1/2$ the size of the original graph, resulting in a logarithmic recursion depth.
[src:logspace/reachability] At each level of the recursion, only linear work is needed to identify the separators as well as the connections possible between vertices.
[src:logspace/reachability] The overall result is $O(n\log n)$ preprocessing time with only $O(\log {n})$ additional information stored for each vertex.
[src:logspace/reachability] An even faster method for pre-processing, due to T.
[src:logspace/reachability] If G exhibits these properties, then we can preprocess the graph in only $O(n)$ time, and store only $O(\log {n})$ extra bits per vertex, answering reachability queries for any pair of vertices in $O(1)$ time with a simple comparison.
[src:logspace/reachability] Preprocessing performs the following steps.
[src:logspace/reachability] We add a new vertex s which has an edge to each 0-indegree vertex, and another new vertex t with edges from each 0-outdegree vertex.
[src:logspace/reachability] Note that the properties of G allow us to do so while maintaining planarity, that is, there will still be no edge crossings after these additions.
[src:logspace/reachability] For each vertex we store the list of adjacencies (out-edges) in order of the planarity of the graph (for example, clockwise with respect to the graph's embedding).
[src:logspace/reachability] We then initialize a counter $i=n+1$ and begin a Depth-First Traversal from s .
[src:logspace/reachability] During this traversal, the adjacency list of each vertex is visited from left-to-right as needed.
[src:logspace/reachability] As vertices are popped from the traversal's stack, they are labelled with the value i , and i is then decremented.
[src:logspace/reachability] Note that t is always labelled with the value $n+1$ and s is always labelled with 0 .
[src:logspace/reachability] The depth-first traversal is then repeated, but this time the adjacency list of each vertex is visited from right-to-left.
[src:logspace/reachability] When completed, s and t , and their incident edges, are removed.
[src:logspace/reachability] Each remaining vertex stores a 2-dimensional label with values from 1 to n .
[src:logspace/reachability] The main result of this method then states that v is reachable from u if and only if $L(u)<L(v)$ , which is easily calculated in $O(1)$ time.
[src:logspace/reachability] A related problem is to solve reachability queries with some number k of vertex failures.
[src:logspace/reachability] For example: "Can vertex u still reach vertex v even though vertices $s_{1},s_{2},...,s_{k}$ have failed and can no longer be used?" A similar problem may consider edge failures rather than vertex failures, or a mix of the two.
[src:logspace/reachability] The breadth-first search technique works just as well on such queries, but constructing an efficient oracle is more challenging.
[src:logspace/reachability] Another problem related to reachability queries is in quickly recalculating changes to reachability relationships when some portion of the graph is changed.
[src:logspace/reachability] For example, this is a relevant concern to garbage collection which needs to balance the reclamation of memory (so that it may be reallocated) with the performance concerns of the running application.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This problem is also called the **undirected reachability problem**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] It does not matter whether many-one reducibility or Turing reducibility is used.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Although originally described in terms of symmetric Turing machines, that equivalent formulation is very complex, and the reducibility definition is what is used in practice.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] USTCON is a special case of STCON (*directed reachability*), the problem of determining whether a directed path between two vertices in a directed graph exists, which is complete for NL.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Because USTCON is **SL**-complete, most advances that impact USTCON have also impacted **SL**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Thus they are connected, and discussed together.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In October 2004 Omer Reingold showed that **SL** = **L**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] SL was first defined in 1982 by Harry R.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Lewis and Christos Papadimitriou, who were looking for a class in which to place USTCON, which until this time could, at best, be placed only in NL, despite seeming not to require nondeterminism.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] where L is the more well-known class of problems solvable by an ordinary deterministic Turing machine in logarithmic space, and NL is the class of problems solvable by nondeterministic Turing machines in logarithmic space.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] The result of Reingold, discussed later, shows that in fact, when limited to log space, the symmetric Turing machine is equivalent in power to the deterministic Turing machine.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] By definition, USTCON is complete for SL (all problems in SL reduce to it, including itself).
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Many more interesting complete problems were found, most by reducing directly or indirectly from USTCON, and a compendium of them was made by Àlvarez and Greenlaw.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Many of the problems are graph theory problems on undirected graphs.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] The complements of all these problems are in SL as well, since, as we will see, SL is closed under complement.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In this sense this class has become somewhat trivial.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] There are well-known classical algorithms such as depth-first search and breadth-first search which solve USTCON in linear time and space.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Their existence, shown long before **SL** was defined, proves that **SL** is contained in **P**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] It's also not difficult to show that USTCON, and so **SL**, is in **NL**, since we can just nondeterministically guess at each vertex which vertex to visit next in order to discover a path if one exists.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] The first nontrivial result for **SL**, however, was Savitch's theorem, proved in 1970, which provided an algorithm that solves USTCON in log2 *n* space.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Unlike depth-first search, however, this algorithm is impractical for most applications because of its potentially superpolynomial running time.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] One consequence of this is that USTCON, and so **SL**, is in DSPACE(log2*n*).
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] False rejections are made with a small bounded probability that shrinks exponentially the longer the random walk is continued.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This showed that **SL** is contained in RLP, the class of problems solvable in polynomial time and logarithmic space with probabilistic machines that reject incorrectly less than 1/3 of the time.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] By replacing the random walk by a universal traversal sequence, Aleliunas et al. also showed that **SL** is contained in L/poly, a non-uniform complexity class of the problems solvable deterministically in logarithmic space with polynomial advice.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In 1989, Borodin et al. strengthened this result by showing that the complement of USTCON, determining whether two vertices are in different connected components, is also in **RLP**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This placed USTCON, and **SL**, in co-**RLP** and in the intersection of **RLP** and co-**RLP**, which is ZPLP, the class of problems which have log-space, expected polynomial-time, no-error randomized algorithms.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In 1992, Nisan, Szemerédi, and Wigderson finally found a new deterministic algorithm to solve USTCON using only log1.5 *n* space.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This was improved slightly, but there would be no more significant gains until Reingold.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In 1995, Nisan and Ta-Shma showed the surprising result that **SL** is closed under complement, which at the time was believed by many to be false; that is, **SL** = co-**SL**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Equivalently, if a problem can be solved by reducing it to a graph and asking if two vertices are in the *same* component, it can also be solved by reducing it to another graph and asking if two vertices are in *different* components.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] However, Reingold's paper would later make this result redundant.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] One of the most important corollaries of **SL** = co-**SL** is that **L****SL** = **SL**; that is, a deterministic, log-space machine with an oracle for **SL** can solve problems in **SL** (trivially) but cannot solve any other problems.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This means it does not matter whether we use Turing reducibility or many-one reducibility to show a problem is in **SL**; they are equivalent.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In 2004, a breakthrough paper by Omer Reingold showed that USTCON is in fact in **L**.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This paper used expander graphs to guide the search through the input graph.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Since USTCON is **SL**-complete, Reingold's result implies that **SL** = **L**, essentially eliminating the usefulness of consideration of **SL** as a separate class.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] A few weeks later, graduate student Vladimir Trifonov showed that USTCON could be solved deterministically using $O{\text{(log }}n{\text{log log }}n)$ space—a weaker result—using different techniques.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] There has not been substantial effort into turning Reingold's algorithm for USTCON into a practical formulation.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] It is explicit in his paper (and those leading up to it) that they are primarily concerned with asymptotics; as a result, the algorithm he describes would actually take $64^{32}\,\log N$ memory, and $O(N^{64^{32}})$ time.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] This means that even for $N=2$ , the algorithm would require more memory than contained on all computers in the world (a kiloexaexaexabyte).
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] The collapse of **L** and **SL** has a number of significant consequences.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] Most obviously, all **SL**-complete problems are now in **L**, and can be gainfully employed in the design of deterministic log-space and polylogarithmic-space algorithms.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] In particular, we have a new set of tools to use in log-space reductions.
[src:logspace/sl-complexity] It is also now known that a problem is in **L** if and only if it is log-space reducible to USTCON.
